<div class="prose">

<p>Every major assessment in this course is scored against three strands. They appear as a triplet — for example, "K/U 7 · T/T 6 · C 7" — not as a single combined grade. Each strand carries forward from unit to unit: your K/U score on the Unit 0 Source Dossier predicts your K/U on every subsequent assessment, unless something changes.</p>

<h2>K/U — Knowledge & Understanding</h2>

<p><em>The student recalls facts, terms and definitions while also explaining concepts, ideas, processes, and themes. The student learns and performs skills related to their studies.</em></p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>7–8 Exemplary</th>
      <th>5–6 Proficient</th>
      <th>3–4 Developing</th>
      <th>1–2 Limited</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>OPVL applied thoroughly to every source. Source types correctly identified (peer-reviewed vs. news vs. corporate vs. AI). Discipline-specific vocabulary (origin, purpose, value, limitations, sycophancy, hallucination, training cutoff) used precisely. AI Documentation Template filled out completely and accurately.</td>
      <td>All four OPVL letters addressed for each source; minor imprecision in one or two sub-elements. Source types correctly identified. Vocabulary used accurately most of the time. AI Documentation Template substantially complete with minor gaps.</td>
      <td>Some knowledge of OPVL but with gaps. One or two letters consistently weaker than others (often Limitations is the weakest). Source-type identification sometimes imprecise. Vocabulary inconsistent. AI Documentation Template partially complete or unevenly applied.</td>
      <td>Little knowledge of OPVL. Multiple letters missing or treated superficially. Source types not distinguished or misidentified. Vocabulary largely absent or misused. AI Documentation Template missing or trivially completed.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>T/T — Thinking & Transfer</h2>

<p><em>The student plans for learning by formulating questions, generating ideas, and researching. The student thinks critically by analysing, interpreting, evaluating, and using other metacognitive skills. The student applies knowledge and skills to unfamiliar or new contexts.</em></p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>7–8 Exemplary</th>
      <th>5–6 Proficient</th>
      <th>3–4 Developing</th>
      <th>1–2 Limited</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>OPVL evaluations identify substantive, specific limitations — not generic ones. The AI source's evaluation names at least one specific thing the AI got wrong, with evidence. Cross-source synthesis identifies non-obvious agreements and disagreements between sources of different types. Critical evaluation, not uncritical reporting.</td>
      <td>Most evaluations are substantive; one may be more generic than the others. The AI source's evaluation identifies a real limitation but may be less specific. Cross-source synthesis is present and accurate but covers expected rather than non-obvious points.</td>
      <td>Evaluations skew generic ("this source might be biased") rather than specific ("this source is funded by the manufacturer of the product it studies"). AI source's limitation is vague ("AI can be wrong") rather than specific. Cross-source synthesis is superficial — restating what each source says without comparing.</td>
      <td>OPVL evaluations are generic or absent. The AI source is treated as if it were just another reliable source, or no real limitation is identified. Cross-source synthesis is missing or merely lists what each source says with no comparison.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>C — Communication</h2>

<p><em>The student expresses and organises ideas in multiple forms. The student adapts communication appropriately to different audiences and forms. The student uses conventions, terminology, and vocabulary relevant to the discipline.</em></p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>7–8 Exemplary</th>
      <th>5–6 Proficient</th>
      <th>3–4 Developing</th>
      <th>1–2 Limited</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Extremely clear with a logical, easy-to-follow structure. Ideas fully developed and presented concisely. Scientific and OPVL-specific vocabulary used precisely throughout. Sources cited consistently and integrated effectively (not just listed). Defense well-paced; Q&amp;A responses confident, substantive, and specific.</td>
      <td>Mainly clear with a mostly logical structure. Ideas mostly developed; concise enough for the audience. Vocabulary precise most of the time. Citations proficient with minor inconsistencies. Defense delivers content clearly; Q&amp;A responses clear but may miss some depth.</td>
      <td>Somewhat clear; structure attempted but result not always easy to follow. Ideas generally developed but may lack concision or detail. Some vocabulary used correctly but with significant errors. Citations have errors or inconsistencies. Defense delivery uneven; Q&amp;A responses partial.</td>
      <td>Unclear. Ideas underdeveloped. Beginner-level vocabulary. Citations missing or unreliable. Defense lacks structure; Q&amp;A responses minimal or off-topic.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Two gates to know about</h2>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">K/U gate — AI Documentation completeness</div>
  If the AI Documentation Template is missing or trivially completed, K/U cannot exceed 3–4 regardless of how strong the rest of the work is. The protocol is non-negotiable.
</div>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">T/T gate — "one thing the AI got wrong"</div>
  If you can't identify a specific AI failure, T/T cannot exceed 5–6 regardless of how strong the traditional-source OPVL is. This is the metacognitive move T/T is designed to detect.
</div>

<h2>How strand scores carry forward</h2>

<p>The Unit 0 strand triplet is a diagnostic for the year. The pattern to watch is <strong>K/U 7–8 paired with T/T 3–4</strong> — knowing OPVL well but not applying it critically to AI. That same pattern, left unaddressed, becomes the failure mode that limits engineering reasoning in Unit 3's Engineering Portfolio. If you see that pattern in your own scores, ask about the extra T/T scaffolding before Unit 1 starts.</p>

</div>
